==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Io
<hw>I"o</hw> <pr>(⟦emac⟧"⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>'Iw`</grk>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In Greek mythology, the
beautiful daughter of Inachus, king of Argos, Greece, who was changed by
Hera (Juno), in a fit of jealousy, into a white heifer, and placed under
the watch of Argus of the hundred eyes.⟦br⟧
When Argus was killed by Hermes at the command of Zeus, the heifer was
maddened by a terrible gadfly sent by Hera, and wandered about until she
arrived in Egypt. There she recovered her original shape, and bore
Epaphus to Zeus. Epaphus became the ancestor of ⟦AE⟧gyptus, Damaus,
Cepheus, and Phineus. She was identified by the Egyptians with Isis.
According to another legend, Io was carried off by Phoenician traders
who landed in Argos. The myth is generally explained to be Aah or the
moon wandering in the starry skies, symbolized by the hundred-eyed
Argus; her transformation into a horned heifer representing the crescent
moon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Century Dict. 1906</source>]</p>

<p><q>Greek mythology, too, knew her [Astarte] as I⟦ocir⟧ and Europa,
and she was fitly symbolised by the cow whose horns resemble the supine
lunar crescent as seen in the south.</q> <rj><qau>Seyce (Anc. Empires,
p. 195).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Century Dict. 1906</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of the large moons of the planet Jupiter,
remarkable for its intense volcanic activity, as observed in fly-bys of
space probes. It was named after the mythological Io.</def> <note>The
remarkable images of Io and Jupiter obtained by the Galileo 2 space
probe to Jupiter and Hubble photographs are available at the web site of
<a href="http://www.nasa.gov">NASA</a>.</note>
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iod-</ent>⟦br⟧
